title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory Lightweight Champion Operator .45
postcontent:
One of my favorites sits and no longer gets love, so up she goes to someone who can love and appreciate her more than I can.  

I bought this Springfield Armory Lightweight Champion Operator .45 brand new in 2009 and have shot it four times, for a grand total of 200 rounds through it.  She's been carried a few times, but has mainly resided in the safe and well kept and cared for.  I had the hammer, sear, disconnector, sear spring and hammer spring upgraded to Nighthawk tool steel parts, and the trigger was also cleaned up to eliminate any creep and to break cleaner than factory. You'd have to feel the trigger to know what I'm talking about.  Night sights are factory and very bright, and the pistol shoots amazingly well. I also had the plastic mainspring housing and ILS lock removed and replaced it with an all steel Nighthawk flat mainspring housing, and the feed ramp was hand polished to ensure reliability.  I hate to see this pistol go, but she must.

Besides the pistol, it will come with all factory goodies (plastic case, manual, factory magazines), five (5) Wilson Combat 47D magazines (four stainless and one black with a flat floorplate to fit the gun for carry), and a a right hand black DeSantis three slot pancake holster which is very comfortable for all day wear.  Basically, this gun's ready to be carried the moment you get it.  It was meticulously cleaned and lubed after every range session using Hoppe's 9 and Shooter's Choice grease.  

Also, there is a slight idiot mark on the slide above the takedown lever, but otherwise the pistol is in excellent condition.  There is 3M Stair Tread tape on the frontstrap for traction, and rubber o-rings on the grip bushings to ensure the grip screws don't back out.

They're getting harder and harder to find, and the upgrades from MIM to tool steel make this a pistol worthy of passing down to your son or daughter when it's time.

Asking $1100 FIRM / CASH ONLY and you MUST have a Washington State driver's license and valid concealed pistol license to buy.  No trades at all, please; only interested in selling this pistol.  Also, I live in Pierce County and am willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet you.  

I am hoping for a quick sale so if you are free today and would like to see or buy this pistol, please text me for best results as I will be in and out all day.  Text only to 253 six eight zero 98 seven seven.

Thank you for looking!  I look forward to hearing from you!

title: For Sale/Trade:  CBC Nylon 66
location: Rye Brook, New York, United States
postcontent:
This is a fun rifle, cleaned up and shoots well.  It has been fun to shoot, however I have too many .22's and the kids do not really shoot any more.  I would consider trades, sks or 91/30 etc...

In 1926, Italian-born immigrants Costabile and Gianicola Matarazzo decided to begin manufacture of their own shot shells and metallic cartridges instead of using imported ones and – thus – the Fabrica Nacional de Cartuchos e Municoes (F.N.C.M.) was born. Their production of 7x57mm ammunition, then in use by the Brazilian Army, by 1932, reaches 30,000 rounds/day.
In 1936 the company is taken over by the DuPerial group, a joint-venture between USA’s Remington Arms and Britain’s Imperial Chemical Industries (ICI) and its name is changed to Companhia Brasileira de Cartuchos (CBC). The arrival of American-made equipment, in 1938, enables CBC to increase its daily output of 7x57mm cartridges from 30,000 to 100,000. With the beginning of World War II in 1939, all of its output is directed to the Brazilian military.
Production of .22 Long Rifle ammunition begins in 1953 with a yearly output of 2.5 million rounds. By 1957 this figure had reached 23 million rounds/year.
Year 1960 saw the beginning of firearms production, with technology supplied by Remington Arms. In 1962 production of the Brazilian version of the Remington Nylon 66 rifle begins. Exports of single-shot break-open shotguns to the USA begin in 1966.
In 1979 CBC was nationalized with 70% of its shares being bought by its directors, Messrs. Libero Cerroti, Leonardo Galassi and Tiberio Stein. The remaining 30% were bought by IMBEL (Industria Brasileira de Material Belico), an Army-owned company (which, today, makes the M.1911-type pistols sold by Springfield Armory).
With DuPont’s Nylon no longer available for manufacture of the Nylon 66 rifle, CBC contacts Rhodia (chemical and pharmaceutical company belonging to the Rhone-Poulenc group) for a replacement material and Rhodia develops a virtually similar polymer specially for CBC.

title: For Sale:  Buffalo Bore Ammo - Heavy .44 Magnum +P+ Ammo - 340 gr. L.F.N. - G.C. (1,478 fps/M.E. 1,649 ft. lbs.) - 20 Round Box
postcontent:
https://www.extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_list&c=9

This new load is designed for only certain revolvers that have the cylinder length to handle it. They are as follows; Ruger Red Hawk, Ruger Super Red Hawk, Ruger Super Blackhawk or Vaquero, Freedom Arms Model 83, Taurus Raging Bull, Colt Anaconda and Dan Wesson Revolvers. Suitable rifles include T/C Encore, "modified" Marlin 1894, Winchester 1894, any rifle with a falling block action and the Handi Rifle. 

What do we mean above by "modified" Marlin? Marlin (for an unknown, not well thought out reason) is using a very slow rate of twist (1/38 inches) on their 1894 chambered in 44 mag. Because of this slow rate of twist, the heaviest bullet that the factory Marlin will stabilize is about 270grs. Other firearm makers that chamber for the 44 mag all use a much faster rate of twist so that their guns will stabilize and therefore accurately shoot bullets over 300grs. Many folks today want their 44 magnums to be able to utilize the heavy 300gr. and heavier bullets - Marlin has not figured this out. If you want decent accuracy out of our new +p+ load in a Marlin, it will need to be re-barreled with a twist rate of roughly 1/20 inch. I have Dave Clay re-barrel all my Marlin 1894's with a faster twist barrel. A 44 magnum that wont accurately shoot 300gr. or heavier bullets is useless to me. Call him at REDACTED for pricing.

This load brings a level of power to the 44 mag. that has never before been known.

This is the cheapest price you will ever see for a FN FNC para.The FN, FNC (Fabrique Nationale carbine) assualt rifle is regarded as one of the best assault rifles ever convceived. The FNC uses a reliable, regulated gas piston design similar to that found on high end AR's but more commonly with the AK-47 and FAL style battle rifles. The FNC is the predecessor to the new FN SCAR. The FNC uses any US M-16 or AR style magazines but also has a specific magazine made by FN, the FNC steel magazines with a metal follower.This model is the Paratrooper folding stock variant. This design is a favorite among collectors. This model also has an integrated, notched, flip up grenade launcher and sight that automatically redirects gas to fire the grenades when the sight is flipped up. The gas system on the FNC is able to be regulated for pressure. The US M249 Squad Automatic Weapon, is loosly based on the FNC design. Overall condition is excellent, the barrel is 1/12 not 1/7 .see photos. Will only sell face to face in Washington state at this price.

postcontent:
Walther P22 Target Model with 5 inch barrel

Includes:
3  ten round magazines, 2 with finger rest extension, 1 without
(the magazine without the finger rest does not hold open the slide after last round due to modifications)
Basic aftermarket hard case. (Plano)

The pistol functions great.  It has been used in NSSF competitions and will hold its own against target model Rugers and Brownings. The 5 inch barrel allows it to cycle reliably with standard velocity ammo and even some subsonics.

One of the magazines has an issue. It was modified in an attempt to increase capacity, but the modification failed.  Thus it will hold 11 rounds, but will only actually feed 10 of them.  Thus it has a snap cap (dummy round) that just stays in it as the last round.  It still functions fine as a 10 round magazine, it just looks a little funny.

This has been my "everything gun" for a few years; competition, home defense, hiking/camping, and daily concealed carry.  I have recently acquired a S&W M&P and have decided to stick with that for future competition and home defense. Thus I am selling the Walther so I can get a dedicated CC pistol and/or another rifle.

Due to new laws in CO, we must use an FFL to run a background check for the transfer. I have one in town I like to use, or I can meet at one of your choice. I will pay half the transfer fee up to $20. (Don't even bother asking me to make the sale without a background check.  As much as I hate the new laws, its not worth risking my rights and my security clearance over a matter of $20.)

postcontent: Here is my post ww2 mosin nagant PU sniper rifle. I've had this for about two years now and I was never a great shot with it. It has a near perfect bore, which is quite shiny, and improved action. The action was improved to help cycle rounds better, and for most ammo I've used, it's quite smooth. There are some rounds that it doesn't like, but I've mostly used silver tip Bulgarian surplus (I've cleaned the rifle thoroughly after shooting to prevent corrosion). There are a few parts of the stock that were messed up from shipping, but if you wish to refinish the stock it would be easy. The rifle is a 1943 Izhevsk with the scope serial number matching the secondary serial number on the side of the receiver. The scope is in fantastic shape despite being almost as old as the rifle. It is Soviet made scope from Omsk plant 325 "progress", it has refubish mark on it and I think the mount is a reproduction. This is one of the earlier rifles imported from the Molot factory into the USA. Overall, the rifle is in fantastic shape and needs somebody to appreciate it more than I do. I will throw in a soft case and 20 rounds of Bulgarian surplus ammo. I will send additional photos upon request.

title: For Sale:  8mm Gew.88 Mauser/Steyr Collectors Rifle
postcontent:
This one has history! 
It's a Steyr Gewehr 88 from 1890, way before WWI when the German Empire still had a Kaiser (emperor) and looks to be having used in the fight with the Ottoman Empire (Persia, now Iran). It is also often erroneously referred to as “Mauser” or “Mannlicher”.

It has all the hallmarks and markings that make this a rifle to have, from the Emperor's crown to the Ottoman insignia. 

Kaiser Wilhelm II was Germany's last emperor and this baby could have seen action in Iran, then the 1st World War, on to WWII.

The bore's rifling is still exceptional an the rifling twist is incredible, especially with this extra long barrel. Rounds chamber tight and the rifle works flawlessly, we shot 2 boxes and the accuracy is incredible! You can actually see those 8mm extra large bullets hit where they impact, even at a distance. Speaking of which, it has a flip up sight for long range shots. Whatever you hit with this baby, it's going down hard...

With the sight in regular mode, it is sighted to 273 yards, then you can flip it up and it's range is from 500 yards, with approx. 110 yard increments to a total range of 2187 yards.

5 shot clip, which can be strip loaded for fast reloading...

At 124 years of age this puppy will give most modern rifles a run for the money especially in accuracy, my buddy with his scoped rifle couldn't believe the distances that this will hit at, without even a scope.

REAL German quality, even after a 124 years, it becomes very apparent when shooting it.

While you can just hang it on your wall as a show off rife, it will be a real joy to shoot, take it hunting and show your buddies how it's done Old School...

You WILL NOT run across another one like, it is very rare...

Cash Only!  $600 OBO
